<h1>@HI{{kitto/tabunn/moshikashitara}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> <strong>@HI{{kitto}}</strong> V ...
<li> <strong>@HI{{kitto}}</strong> V ... @HI{{deshou}}
<li> <strong>@HI{{tabunn}}</strong> V ...
<li> <strong>@HI{{tabunn}}</strong> V ... @HI{{deshou}}
<li> <strong>@HI{{moshikashitara}}</strong> V ...
<li> <strong>@HI{{moshikashitara}}</strong> V ... @HI{{kamoshiremasenn}}

</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{kitto}}</strong> indicates a high degree of certainty. It can be used with @HI{{deshou}}.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{tabunn}}</strong> implies less certainty than when <strong>@HI{{kitto}}</strong> is used. It is most often
used with @HI{{deshou}}.
</p>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{moshikashitara}}</strong> is most often used with @HI{{kamo shiremasenn}}. Of the threee adverbs described here,
this one involves the least amount of certainty.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{mira-}}sanha <strong>kitto</strong> @KJ{{come}}masu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Mr. Miller will surely come.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{mountain^rice*field}}sanha kono@KT{{nyu-su}}wo <strong>tabunn</strong> @KJ{{know}}ranai
      to @KJ{{think}}imasu.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I guess Mr. Yamada does not know this news.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{<strong>moshikashitara</strong> 3@KJ{{month}}ni @KJ{{graduate^business}}dekinai kamo shiremasen.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      There is a chance I might be unable to graduate in March.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

